{"Body":"<p>Hebrew is not strictly Indo-Eurpoean (although <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ghil%27ad_Zuckermann#Historical_linguistics_-_characterization_of_Israeli_Hebrew\" rel=\"nofollow\">some</a> argue it is), but it has something similar: the fricatives /v/, /χ/ and /f/ (when represented by the letters ב, כ and פ) become the plosives /b/, /k/ and /p/ when they come at the start of the word, or after some prepositions, but not after other prepositions. This is called a <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dagesh#Dagesh_Kal\" rel=\"nofollow\">Dagesh Kal</a>.</p>\n\n<p>For example,</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>כּלב <em>kelev</em>: dog</p>\n  \n  <p>הכּלב <em>hakelev</em>: the dog</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>but,</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>לכלב <em>leχelev</em>: for/to a dog</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "Id":"75", "ParentId":"9", "LastEditorUserId":"100", "CreationDate":"2011-09-14T05:48:38.840", "OwnerUserId":"100", "PostTypeId":"2", "comments":[], "LastEditDate":"2011-09-14T19:16:51.550", "LastEditedUser":{"UpVotes":"84", "Location":"Israel", "DownVotes":"0", "Id":"100", "AccountId":"78446", "Views":"6", "Reputation":"244", "CreationDate":"2011-09-14T04:37:43.120", "DisplayName":"Daniel Hershcovich", "LastAccessDate":"2014-01-16T20:01:10.310", "Age":"23"}, "LastActivityDate":"2011-09-14T19:16:51.550", "Score":"-4", "CommentCount":"9", "OwnerUser":{"UpVotes":"84", "Location":"Israel", "DownVotes":"0", "Id":"100", "AccountId":"78446", "Views":"6", "Reputation":"244", "CreationDate":"2011-09-14T04:37:43.120", "DisplayName":"Daniel Hershcovich", "LastAccessDate":"2014-01-16T20:01:10.310", "Age":"23"}}